                <head>134. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>At the 380th meeting of the National Security Council on September 25, Deputy
                    Director of Central Intelligence <persName corresp="#p_CGCP1">C. P.
                        Cabell</persName> briefed the Council on significant world developments
                    affecting U.S. security. Cabell briefly referred to Cuba, noting that <persName
                        corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>’s rebel movement “was in a stronger
                    position than ever before.” There was no other discussion of the Cuban
                    situation. (Memorandum of discussion; Eisenhower Library, Whitman File, <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Records)</p>
            </div>
